1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
========================================================================

UNJYNX light mode is NOT an afterthought. It is a PARALLEL design system
where the app feels like warm morning silk versus midnight velvet. The core
insight: premium apps NEVER use pure white (#FFFFFF). They use warm tinted
backgrounds that feel intentional and branded.

KEY DECISIONS:
- Background: #F8F5FF (Purple Mist) -- warm purple-tinted off-white
- Text: #1A0533 (Midnight Purple) -- 17.51:1 contrast ratio (AAA)
- Gold: #B8860B (Rich Gold) -- deepened from #FFD700 which washes out on light
- Shadows: Purple-tinted rgba(26,5,51,x) -- NEVER generic gray
- Glass: 65% white opacity + 8px blur + purple border (vs 8% + 12px in dark)
- Particles: 30% of dark mode count, 50% movement, deeper tints

COMPETITIVE EDGE:
- Todoist light: Pure #FFFFFF bg, gray text, red accent. Generic.
- Notion light: #FFFFFF main, #F7F6F3 sidebar. Intentionally bland.
- TickTick light: Blue accent on white. Every app does this.
- Things 3 light: Blue accent only. No personality.
- UNJYNX light: #F8F5FF bg, #1A0533 text, #B8860B gold, purple-tinted everything.
  Nobody does this. It is warm, branded, and unmistakably UNJYNX.

This document provides the mathematical, scientific, and competitive
justification for every design decision in UNJYNX light mode.

========================================================================
2. WHY #F8F5FF — THE SCIENCE OF WARM OFF-WHITE
========================================================================

2.1 THE PROBLEM WITH PURE WHITE

Pure white (#FFFFFF) emits maximum light at full RGB (255, 255, 255).
On modern OLED and high-brightness LCD displays, this creates:

- Luminance fatigue: The eye pupil contracts more on pure white, causing
  faster eye strain during extended use (30+ minutes)
- Clinical sterility: Pure white is associated with hospitals, fluorescent
  offices, and institutional spaces -- not premium product experiences
- Brand invisibility: White provides zero brand signal. It is the absence
  of design decision, not the presence of one.
- Glow bleed: On OLED panels, pure white pixels emit maximum light that
  bleeds into adjacent dark elements, reducing perceived sharpness

2.2 THE SCIENCE OF #F8F5FF

Hex: #F8F5FF
RGB: (248, 245, 255)
HSL: (258 degrees, 100%, 98%)

The key is the hue: 258 degrees places it firmly in the purple spectrum.
At 98% lightness, it is almost white -- but the 100% saturation means
the purple tint is REAL, not imagined. Users perceive it subconsciously.

Color science research shows:
- Tinted neutrals feel warmer and more intentional than pure neutrals
- Purple specifically evokes: creativity, luxury, wisdom, spirituality
- At 98% lightness, the tint is felt, not seen -- it operates below
  conscious awareness but above indifference
- The Delta E (color difference) between #F8F5FF and #FFFFFF is ~3.2,
  which is noticeable at a glance per CIE standards

2.3 COMPETITIVE VALIDATION

TODOIST:  #FFFFFF -- Pure white. No tint. Generic.
NOTION:   #FFFFFF main / #F7F6F3 sidebar -- Warm gray sidebar, but main is white.
           Notion sidebar (#F7F6F3) has a YELLOW tint (43 degrees), not purple.
THINGS 3: #FFFFFF -- Pure white with blue accents only.
ARC:      Uses warm tinted backgrounds that shift by space.
CRAFT:    Uses #FAFAF9 -- very slight warm tint, Stone-50 equivalent.
BEAR:     Uses warm cream tones -- editorial/note-taking aesthetic.
AMIE:     Uses colorful backgrounds per context -- playful but inconsistent.

UNJYNX:   #F8F5FF -- Purple-tinted. Branded. Consistent. Warm without being
           yellow/cream (which would clash with our purple brand).

2.4 TAILWIND CSS VALIDATION

Tailwind CSS defines purple-50 as #FAF5FF -- nearly identical to our #F8F5FF.
This means our background color is already in the vocabulary of millions of
developers worldwide. It is established but not overused.

Our #F8F5FF is 2 points warmer (F8 vs FA in red channel) which makes it
very slightly more pink-purple than Tailwind blue-purple. This subtle
warmth is what makes it feel like morning silk rather than cold lavender.

