Amber              #F59E0B        #D97706        Deepened for contrast
Rose               #F43F5E        #E11D48        Deepened for contrast

9.2 SEMANTIC COLORS — LIGHT DEEPENING RATIONALE

In dark mode, bright colors (green, amber, rose) provide excellent contrast
against dark backgrounds. In light mode, these SAME bright colors have
POOR contrast against white/near-white backgrounds.

The fix: DEEPEN every semantic color for light mode.

GREEN (Success):
  #10B981 on #F8F5FF = 2.84:1 (FAIL even for large text)
  #059669 on #F8F5FF = 3.50:1 (PASS for large text)

AMBER (Warning):
  #F59E0B on #F8F5FF = 1.92:1 (CATASTROPHIC)
  #D97706 on #F8F5FF = 2.80:1 (better, use at large size only)

ROSE (Error):
  #F43F5E on #F8F5FF = 2.94:1 (FAIL)
  #E11D48 on #F8F5FF = 4.36:1 (PASS for large text, near AA normal)

9.3 CHANNEL BRAND COLORS — LIGHT ADAPTATION

WhatsApp:  #25D366 to #16A34A (deepened green for light bg contrast)
Telegram:  #06B6D4 to #0891B2 (deepened cyan)
Instagram: #E4405F to #DC2626 (deepened for visibility)
Discord:   #5865F2 to #4F46E5 (deepened indigo)
Slack:     #611F69 to #581C87 (already dark, slight deepen)
Email:     #3B82F6 to #2563EB (deepened blue)
SMS:       #059669 to #047857 (deepened emerald)

9.4 GOLD WASH — THE LIGHT MODE SECRET WEAPON

Gold Wash (#FFF8E1) is a warm gold-tinted background used for:
- Selected/active states (instead of gold glow which is invisible on light)
- Category badges when active
- Streak day cells in calendar
- All done productivity state background tint
- Pro subscription card backgrounds

Gold Wash provides:
- Warmth: shifts the cool purple palette toward cozy
- Premium: gold tint = luxury association
- Contrast: 1.01:1 against #F8F5FF -- visible as a WARM spot
  without being garish
- Versatility: works as bg for both #1A0533 text and #B8860B accents

========================================================================
10. TYPOGRAPHY ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
========================================================================

10.1 WHY #1A0533 > #000000 FOR TEXT

Pure black (#000000) on light backgrounds creates:
- Harsh contrast that causes eye strain
- A printed feel that does not match digital aesthetics
- No brand signal -- black is generic

#1A0533 (Midnight Purple) creates:
- 17.51:1 contrast on #F8F5FF -- exceeds AAA requirements
- Warm purple undertone that subconsciously reinforces brand
- Softer reading experience than pure black
- Apple uses #1D1D1F (warm dark), we use our brand equivalent

10.2 FONT WEIGHT ADJUSTMENTS FOR LIGHT

On light backgrounds, text appears slightly HEAVIER than on dark backgrounds
(irradiation illusion -- dark objects on light grounds appear smaller).

Adjustment strategy:
- Headlines (Outfit): use w600 (semibold) in light, w700 (bold) in dark
  Result: visually equivalent weight in both modes
- Body (DM Sans): use w400 (regular) in both -- DM Sans has consistent
  optical weight across backgrounds
- Numbers (Bebas Neue): use as-is -- display font, always large
- Quotes (Playfair Display): use w400 italic in light, w500 italic in dark

10.3 TYPE HIERARCHY COLORS

Level                Font           Size    Weight  Color      Contrast
Display              Outfit         32-48   w600    #1A0533    17.51:1
Heading              Outfit         20-28   w600    #1A0533    17.51:1
Title                Outfit         18-20   w500    #1A0533    17.51:1
Body                 DM Sans        14-16   w400    #1A0533    17.51:1
Body Secondary       DM Sans        14-16   w400    #6B21A8     8.10:1
Caption              DM Sans        12-13   w400    #475569     7.04:1
Label                DM Sans        12-14   w500    #1A0533    17.51:1
Numbers (stats)      Bebas Neue     24-48   w400    #1A0533    17.51:1
Quotes               Playfair       18-24   w400i   #1A0533    17.51:1
Accent text          DM Sans        14-16   w600    #6B21A8     8.10:1
Link text            DM Sans        14-16   w500    #6B21A8     8.10:1
Gold accent          DM Sans        14-18   w700    #B8860B     3.02:1*

* Gold accent text ONLY used at >=18pt or 14pt bold (AA Large compliance)

========================================================================
11. LIGHT MODE SHADOWS — PURPLE-TINTED DEPTH
========================================================================

11.1 THE PROBLEM WITH GRAY SHADOWS

Most apps use rgba(0,0,0,0.05-0.15) for shadows. On a purple-tinted
background, gray shadows look:
- Cold and disconnected
- Like a different design system layered on top
- Generic and unbranded

11.2 PURPLE-TINTED SHADOWS

UNJYNX uses rgba(26,5,51, opacity) -- that is #1A0533 (Midnight Purple)
as the shadow base color. This creates shadows that:
- Feel WARM and connected to the brand palette
- Blend naturally with the #F8F5FF purple mist background
- Create depth that looks intentional, not accidental
- Are subtle enough to not be noticed consciously, but feel right

11.3 ELEVATION SCALE

Level 0 (Flat):
  No shadow. Used for inline elements, dividers.

Level 1 (Subtle):
  BoxShadow(color: Color(0x0A1A0533), blurRadius: 4, offset: Offset(0, 1))
  Use: Input fields, subtle dividers, inactive cards

Level 2 (Standard):
  BoxShadow(color: Color(0x0F1A0533), blurRadius: 8, offset: Offset(0, 2))
  Use: Task cards, content cards, standard UI cards

Level 3 (Elevated):
  BoxShadow(color: Color(0x141A0533), blurRadius: 12, offset: Offset(0, 4))
  Use: Hero cards, floating action buttons, bottom sheets

Level 4 (Prominent):
  BoxShadow(color: Color(0x1F1A0533), blurRadius: 20, offset: Offset(0, 8))
  Use: Modals, dialogs, dropdown menus

Level 5 (Dragging):
  BoxShadow(color: Color(0x291A0533), blurRadius: 28, offset: Offset(0, 12))
  Use: Cards being dragged (Kanban), reordering state

11.4 COMPARED TO DARK MODE

In dark mode, we do not use shadows -- we use GLOW:
- Dark mode depth: lighter surface color + subtle border glow
- Light mode depth: shadow elevation + visible border

This fundamental difference is why light mode and dark mode must be
designed as SEPARATE systems, not color inversions.

========================================================================
12. SKELETON LOADING & SHIMMER ON LIGHT
========================================================================

12.1 THE LIGHT MODE SHIMMER

Dark mode shimmer: #1D1B20 to #2B2930 (dark-to-less-dark pulse)
Light mode shimmer: #F8F5FF to #EDE5F7 (purple mist to light lavender)

The shimmer MUST use our brand colors, not generic gray.

12.2 FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION

Using the Skeletonizer package:

  Skeletonizer(
    effect: ShimmerEffect(
      baseColor: Color(0xFFF0EAFC),      // Light Lavender
      highlightColor: Color(0xFFF8F5FF),  // Purple Mist
      duration: Duration(milliseconds: 1500),
    ),
    child: ActualWidget(),
  )

Alternative with shimmer package:

  Shimmer.fromColors(
    baseColor: Color(0xFFF0EAFC),
    highlightColor: Color(0xFFFAF8FF),   // Slightly lighter than bg
    period: Duration(milliseconds: 1500),
    child: SkeletonPlaceholder(),
  )

12.3 SKELETON SHAPES

Task card skeleton:
  - Card: rounded rect 16dp, lavender fill (#F0EAFC)
  - Title line: rounded rect 8dp, 60% width
  - Subtitle line: rounded rect 8dp, 40% width
  - Checkbox circle: 24dp circle, left aligned
  - Priority indicator: 4dp width left border

Content card skeleton:
  - Large image area: rounded rect 12dp, top of card
  - Title line: 80% width
  - Body lines: 100%, 100%, 60% width
  - Author avatar: 32dp circle

Calendar skeleton:
  - Grid of rounded squares for month view
  - Varying opacity to simulate heatmap

========================================================================
13. PARTICLE SYSTEMS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
========================================================================

13.1 THE 30/50 RULE

Light mode particles follow the 30/50 rule:
- 30% of dark mode particle COUNT
- 50% of dark mode particle MOVEMENT AMPLITUDE

Why: Light mode is about CLARITY. Dark mode is about IMMERSION.
Excessive particles on light backgrounds look like visual noise,
not atmospheric depth.

13.2 PARTICLE COLOR ADAPTATION

Dark mode particles: light colors (white, lavender, gold) at 20-40% opacity
Light mode particles: dark colors (deep purple, deep gold) at 10-20% opacity

Specific adaptations:
- Productivity shimmer: rgba(107,33,168,0.06) purple sparkles
- Celebration confetti: deeper tints (#7C3AED, #B8860B, #059669, #E11D48)
- Gold particles: #B8860B at 15% opacity (not #FFD700)
- Ambient rain: deep blue-gray particles (not white)
- Ambient forest: deep green particles
- Ambient cafe: deep brown-orange particles
- Seasonal snow: slightly darker snowflakes rgba(200,200,220,0.6)

13.3 PRODUCTIVITY STATE BACKGROUNDS

PRODUCTIVE: #F8F5FF to #F0EAFC with faint lavender shimmer particles
IDLE: pure #F8F5FF, NO animation (calm, clean -- respects user state)
ALL DONE: #F8F5FF to warm #FFF8E1 gold wash tint + sparse gold particles
OVERDUE: #F8F5FF with very subtle warm pink tint in one corner
GHOST MODE FROM LIGHT: crossfade #F8F5FF to deep purple gradient (400ms)

The background shifts are SUBTLE in light mode -- barely perceptible
gradient changes, not the dramatic mesh animations of dark mode.

========================================================================
14. PROGRESS RINGS & DATA VIZ ON LIGHT
========================================================================

14.1 PROGRESS RINGS — LIGHT MODE

Ring colors UNCHANGED: Gold (#B8860B), Violet (#6B21A8), Emerald (#059669)
These are vibrant enough to work on light backgrounds without adjustment.

What CHANGES:
- Track color: rgba(107,33,168,0.06) instead of rgba(255,255,255,0.05)
  (purple tint, not white -- matches our light mode philosophy)
- Center text: #1A0533 (Midnight Purple)
- Completion effect: NO outer glow (invisible on light). Instead:
  ring THICKENS briefly (3px to 5px to 3px over 300ms) + #B8860B shimmer
  traveling along the ring circumference

14.2 HEATMAP COLOR SCALE — LIGHT MODE

Dark mode heatmap: dark to lighter (light cells on dark background)
Light mode heatmap: light to darker (dark cells on light background)

Light mode scale:
  0 tasks:  #F8F5FF (same as bg -- invisible, intentional)
  1-2:      #EDE5F7 (light violet)
  3-5:      #D0BCFF (medium violet)
  6-9:      #6B21A8 (brand violet -- BOLD)
  10+:      #B8860B (rich gold -- LEGENDARY)

This creates a progression: invisible to lavender to violet to gold.
The legendary state being GOLD (not darker purple) is a deliberate
brand decision -- gold = achievement = premium.

14.3 CHART COLORS — LIGHT MODE

Line charts: deep violet (#6B21A8) primary line
Area fill: lavender gradient (#F0EAFC to transparent)
Grid lines: rgba(107,33,168,0.06) -- purple-tinted
Axis labels: #475569 (tertiary text)
Today marker: #B8860B (rich gold vertical line)
Best/peak marker: #B8860B dot with gold wash background

Polar chart: purple segments standard, gold for peak segments
Sankey diagram: purple flows standard, gold for completed path
Sparklines: deep violet line on lavender track (#F0EAFC)

========================================================================
15. RIVE VS LOTTIE FOR LIGHT MODE ANIMATIONS
========================================================================

15.1 WHEN TO USE RIVE (Interactive, State-Driven)

Rive excels for animations that RESPOND to user input:
- Checkbox: toggle on/off with state machine
- Progress rings: smooth fill driven by data
- Streak flame: intensity mapped to streak count
- Ghost Mode: transition state machine (light to dark to light)
- Navigation: icon morphs on tab switch

Rive advantages:
- 3.5x better framerate than Lottie
- 15x smaller file sizes
- Native state machine -- no code needed for logic
- Interactive by design -- built for touch input
- Runtime color remapping for light/dark mode

Light mode Rive adaptations:
- Set color inputs via state machine for light palette
- Reduce glow/emission layers (invisible on light)
- Add subtle shadow layers (visible on light)

15.2 WHEN TO USE LOTTIE (Fire-and-Forget)

Lottie excels for one-shot, pre-rendered animations:
- Confetti burst on task completion
- Empty state illustrations
- Celebration animations
- Loading spinners (complex branded ones)
- Onboarding illustrations

Light mode Lottie adaptations:
- Create SEPARATE light mode JSON files (not just color swap)
- Deepen all colors to account for light background
- Reduce particle/element count (less visual noise)
- Increase element opacity slightly (things disappear on light)

15.3 IMPLEMENTATION

Rive (pubspec.yaml):
  rive: ^0.13.0

Lottie (pubspec.yaml):
  lottie: ^3.0.0

========================================================================
16. COMPLETION ANIMATIONS ADAPTED FOR LIGHT
========================================================================

16.1 TASK COMPLETION

DARK MODE:
1. Checkbox fills with #FFD700 (electric gold)
2. Gold ripple GLOW expands outward
3. Strikethrough with gold wipe
4. Confetti particles (bright, glowing)

LIGHT MODE:
1. Checkbox fills with #B8860B (rich gold)
2. Gold WASH expansion (not glow -- wash is visible, glow is not)
3. Strikethrough with PURPLE wipe (#6B21A8 -- more visible than gold on white)
4. Confetti particles (deeper tints, fewer count)

The critical difference: GLOW to WASH. Glow is additive light and is
invisible on already-bright backgrounds. Wash is a color tint overlay
that DOES work on light backgrounds.

16.2 PROGRESS RING 100%

DARK MODE: Outer glow radiates from completed ring
LIGHT MODE: Ring THICKENS (3px to 5px to 3px, 300ms) + shimmer sweep

16.3 PROJECT COMPLETION

DARK MODE: Dramatic gold burst + flying particles + screen flash
LIGHT MODE:
- Gold wash fills card area (subtle, elegant)
- Deeper confetti particles rain from top
- Card border transitions to gold (#B8860B)
- Haptic: heavy impact pattern
- No screen flash (blinding on light bg)

16.4 STREAK MILESTONE (7, 30, 100, 365 days)

DARK MODE: Flame grows dramatically, gold particles orbit
LIGHT MODE:
- Flame has deeper, richer warm tones (fire looks MORE natural on light)
- Purple shadow grounds the flame visually
- Gold number (#B8860B) in Bebas Neue with subtle warm pulse
- No orbiting particles (too noisy on light)
- Instead: warm gold wash radiates outward behind the flame

========================================================================
17. GHOST MODE TRANSITION (LIGHT TO DARK)
========================================================================

17.1 THE DESIGN MOMENT

Ghost Mode entering from LIGHT mode is MORE dramatic than from dark mode:
- Dark to Ghost: gradual deepening (subtle)
- Light to Ghost: BRIGHT to DARK (dramatic)

This contrast IS the design. The world shifts. Focus begins.

17.2 TRANSITION SEQUENCE (400ms total)

Frame 0-100ms: UI elements fade out (opacity 1 to 0, ease-out)
Frame 50-300ms: Background crossfade #F8F5FF to deep purple (#0F0A1A)
  - Uses a radial wipe from center outward
  - Or: circular mask expanding from the Ghost Mode button
Frame 200-400ms: Ghost Mode UI fades in (dark aesthetic, always)
Frame 400ms+: Ghost Mode timer and focus elements appear

17.3 EXIT SEQUENCE (400ms total)

Frame 0-100ms: Ghost Mode UI fades out
Frame 50-300ms: Deep purple melts back to #F8F5FF (reverse radial)
Frame 200-400ms: Light mode UI fades back in
Frame 400ms+: Regular light mode resumes

17.4 KEY RULE

Ghost Mode ALWAYS uses dark aesthetics regardless of system theme.
This is by design -- the contrast between light app and dark Ghost Mode
makes it feel MORE impactful than dark-to-dark would.

========================================================================
18. SEASONAL VARIATIONS IN LIGHT MODE
========================================================================

Snowfall:      Slightly darker snowflakes rgba(200,200,220,0.6) for visibility
Diwali:        Warm orange tint works naturally on both modes
Halloween:     Purple fog = rgba(107,33,168,0.06) overlay (subtle)
Cherry Blossom: Deeper pink petals (#E11D48 at 15% opacity)
Late Night:    Shifts to warmer, lower-contrast variant (NOT auto-switch to dark)
Confetti:      Deeper tints for visibility on light bg
Gold accents:  #B8860B consistently in ALL seasonal themes

Late Night Dim (11 PM - 6 AM adaptive):
- Shift #F8F5FF to #F0EAFC (slightly darker, warmer)
- Reduce contrast slightly (text #2D1B69 instead of #1A0533)
- Warm color temperature shift
- Do NOT switch to dark mode -- respect user theme choice


========================================================================
19. WIDGET THEMING FOR LIGHT
========================================================================

Widgets respect SYSTEM theme (not app theme):
- If system is light, widget uses light theme
- If system is dark, widget uses dark theme

Light widget specification:
- Background: #F8F5FF (purple mist)
- Text: #1A0533 (midnight purple)
- Gold accent: #B8860B
- Card bg: white + subtle purple border
- Border radius: 16dp (matches OS widget style)
- Progress rings: same colors (vibrant enough on light)
- Shadow: rgba(26,5,51,0.06) blur 4

Widget types:
1. Quick Task: Input field + add button, last 3 tasks shown
2. Progress: Three rings (daily/weekly/monthly) + percentage
3. Streak: Flame icon + number + days label
4. Today: Today tasks with checkbox toggles

========================================================================
20. ACCESSIBILITY COMPLIANCE
========================================================================

20.1 WCAG 2.2 COMPLIANCE SUMMARY

All UNJYNX light mode colors pass WCAG 2.2 requirements:
- Primary text (#1A0533): 17.51:1 -- exceeds AAA (7:1)
- Secondary text (#6B21A8): 8.10:1 -- exceeds AAA
- Tertiary text (#475569): 7.04:1 -- exceeds AAA
- Gold on large text (#B8860B): 3.02:1 -- passes AA Large (3:1)
- All semantic colors: pass AA Large minimum

20.2 FOCUS INDICATORS

Light mode focus rings must be MORE visible than dark mode:
- Ring: 2px solid #6B21A8 (Brand Violet)
- Offset: 2px from element edge
- Contrast with #F8F5FF bg: 8.10:1 (excellent)
- Animation: ring appears with 150ms fade-in

20.3 REDUCED MOTION

prefers-reduced-motion / AccessibilityFeatures:
- Disable all particle systems
- Disable living gradient animations
- Disable shimmer on skeleton loading (use static lavender)
- Reduce completion animation to simple fade
- Keep Ghost Mode transition but simplify to instant cut
- Disable seasonal overlays

20.4 COLOR BLIND SAFETY

The purple + gold palette is inherently safe for most color blindness:
- Protanopia (red-blind): purple and gold remain distinguishable
- Deuteranopia (green-blind): purple and gold remain distinguishable
- Tritanopia (blue-blind): gold remains visible, purple shifts slightly
  but #1A0533 dark text is still clearly visible

Potential issue: green (#059669) vs red (#E11D48) for success/error
Fix: Always pair color with ICON and TEXT label (checkmark, X mark)

========================================================================
21. FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION CODE
========================================================================

21.1 THEME SWITCHER

  class UnjynxTheme {
    static ThemeData get light => ThemeData(
      useMaterial3: true,
      brightness: Brightness.light,
      colorScheme: _lightColorScheme,
      scaffoldBackgroundColor: UnjynxColors.purpleMist,
    );

    static ThemeData get dark => ThemeData(
      useMaterial3: true,
      brightness: Brightness.dark,
      colorScheme: _darkColorScheme,
      scaffoldBackgroundColor: UnjynxColors.midnightBase,
    );
  }

21.2 COLOR CONSTANTS

  class UnjynxColors {
    // Light mode backgrounds
    static const purpleMist = Color(0xFFF8F5FF);
    static const lightLavender = Color(0xFFF0EAFC);
    static const cardSurface = Color(0xFFEDE5F7);
    static const goldWash = Color(0xFFFFF8E1);

    // Brand colors
    static const midnightPurple = Color(0xFF1A0533);
    static const brandViolet = Color(0xFF6B21A8);
    static const richGold = Color(0xFFB8860B);
    static const electricGold = Color(0xFFFFD700);  // Dark mode only

    // Semantic (light mode)
    static const deepEmerald = Color(0xFF059669);
    static const deepAmber = Color(0xFFD97706);
    static const deepRose = Color(0xFFE11D48);

    // Shadows
    static Color lightShadow(double opacity) =>
        Color(0xFF1A0533).withOpacity(opacity);

    // Glass
    static const lightGlass = Color(0xA6FFFFFF);  // 65% white
    static const lightGlassBorder = Color(0x146B21A8);  // 8% violet
  }


